message: Add content related to Goguryeo and Baekje.
The word ancient Proto-Koreanic has been deleted, and is there any significant difference from the previous descriptions, except for the descriptions of Goguryeo and Baekje?
Sorry for the one-sided argument. However, I will add it as it is because it is a widely known historical fact that Buyeo is the main descendant of Goguryeo and Baekje.

Most Korean and Western linguists at least view the language of Buyeo as similar to Korean, and it cannot be denied that Goguryeo and Baekje were also kingdoms established by the Buyeo people and were ethnically similar to Buyeo.\n\nAlso, Wikipedias of other countries such as Germany, France, Poland and Turkey view Buyeo as Korea's history.

Current mainstream academia in the West and Korea has it that Buyeo was a Proto-Koreanic kingdom constituted by the Koreanic Yemaek tribes. The initiative that Buyeo was tungusic and distinct from Koreanic is currently a contested, unaccepted theory on line with China's Northeast Project.

The term 'Fuyu', is not an officially renowned one used throughout academia worldwide. It is only used in Chinese-speaking countries. The canon term used widely is Buyeo/Puyo, depending on the form of romanization. Meanwhile, records regarding Buyeo and the Xuantu Commandery's diplomatic relations have been edited as there are no indications on a script or archaeological findings that imply a direct form of Chinese dominance. Academia from both West and Korea assess otherwise. (Tributary system)
